Description: CVE-2024-10041 - pam_unix: always use helper for shadow entries
 A vulnerability was found in PAM where secret information (password
 hashes from /etc/shadow) is stored in memory via pam_modutil_getspnam()
 during authentication.  An attacker able to influence the victim
 process can exploit speculative execution (branch predictor / ROP) to
 leak those hashes.
 .
 Upstream fix (b3020da): stop calling pam_modutil_getspnam() from
 pam_unix.so for shadowed accounts and always invoke the setuid helper
 (unix_chkpwd) instead, so hashes are not retained in the calling
 process address space.
 .
 Follow-up (b7b9636): always attempt setuid(0) before exec'ing the
 helper so credential checks still work when the caller has CAP_SETUID
 but geteuid() != 0.
 .
 Backport notes for Debian bullseye (1.4.0-9+deb11u2):
 - passverify.c still has Debian's pam_unix_fix_sgid_shadow_auth
   logic (try getspnam first, helper only on failure); rewrite that
   path to match upstream always-helper semantics.
 - HELPER_COMPILE continues to use pam_modutil_getspnam (macro'd to
   getspnam in the helper build).
