Description: CVE-2026-54411 - pam_userdb: constant-time password comparison
 The pam_userdb module compared the user-supplied password against the
 stored plaintext password using strncmp()/strncasecmp() guarded by a
 strlen() length check.  The length pre-check leaks the password length
 via early exit, and the strncmp/strncasecmp comparisons leak prefix
 bytes through their non-constant-time behaviour (CWE-208 - Observable
 Timing Discrepancy).
 .
 Replace the comparison with a constant-time equality check.  Two
 helpers are added to libpam/include/pam_inline.h:
 pam_consttime_streq (case-sensitive) and pam_consttime_strcaseeq
 (case-insensitive).  Both run for exactly strlen(userinput)+1
 iterations regardless of the secret, eliminating the timing oracle.
 .
 Backport notes for Debian bullseye (1.4.0-9+deb11u2):
 - Upstream already had pam_consttime_streq; v1.4.0 lacks both helpers,
   so both are added here.
 - pam_overwrite_string() is available via Debian's 0018-secure_erase
   backport, matching upstream's use in the pam_userdb change.
Origin: backport, https://github.com/linux-pam/linux-pam/commit/c7e885a4298cf459820bcaf9b657521cbe04825e
Bug: https://github.com/linux-pam/linux-pam/issues/992
Bug: https://github.com/linux-pam/linux-pam/pull/991
